WEBVTT

00:00:00.590 --> 00:00:07.589
We warmly welcome all of you to this month's broadcast.

00:00:07.589 --> 00:00:14.589
Here is just a taste of what we can look forward to on the program.

00:00:14.589 --> 00:00:20.589
A life spent in the full-time ministry is both exciting and challenging.

00:00:20.589 --> 00:00:26.589
We'll meet a brother and his wife who have spent decades in various forms of this service.

00:00:26.589 --> 00:00:31.589
What lessons can we learn from their experiences?

00:00:31.589 --> 00:00:38.590
Then we'll hear the story of a woman who struggled for years with severe drug addiction.

00:00:38.590 --> 00:00:42.590
What would help her eventually break free?

00:00:42.590 --> 00:00:52.590
And our new music video will help us feel the brotherly love we enjoy as a part of Jehovah's organization.

00:00:52.590 --> 00:01:03.590
There's certainly plenty to enjoy on this August 2018 edition of JW Broadcasting.

00:01:03.590 --> 00:01:30.540
The theme for this month's program is appreciating our gifts and men.

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:37.540
Who of us does not enjoy being given a fine, well-chosen gift?

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:48.540
For example, you brothers, do you not take pleasure in receiving a colorful but tasteful 100% silk tie?

00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:55.540
Are you sisters? Do you not delight in being given an exquisite, charming silk scarf?

00:01:55.540 --> 00:02:04.540
But what if you took that silk tie or silk scarf and used it to polish your shoes?

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:12.539
How do you think the giver of your gift would feel if he saw you using his gift in that way?

00:02:12.539 --> 00:02:20.539
Obviously, it would be misused and disrespect for the gift and would insult the giver.

00:02:20.539 --> 00:02:23.539
What is the point of our illustration?

00:02:23.539 --> 00:02:33.539
Will Jehovah and Jesus have given us a fine, well-chosen gift in the form of the elders?

00:02:33.539 --> 00:02:45.539
But as we will discuss, all of us must make sure that we always show appreciation and respect for this divine provision.

00:02:45.539 --> 00:02:51.539
Please turn to Ephesians chapter 4 and verse 8.

00:02:51.539 --> 00:02:59.539
And let's read about this gift that Jehovah and Jesus have given us.

00:02:59.539 --> 00:03:12.539
It reads, for it says, when he ascended on high, he carried away captives. He gave gifts in men.

00:03:12.539 --> 00:03:21.539
You notice, by means of Jesus' perfect integrity, Jesus conquered Satan and his world.

00:03:21.539 --> 00:03:32.539
As a world conqueror, figuratively, he has plundered captives and has given them his gifts to the congregations.

00:03:32.539 --> 00:03:35.539
How useful are these gifts in men?

00:03:35.539 --> 00:03:39.539
Will please look at verses 11 and 12 for the answer.

00:03:39.539 --> 00:03:50.539
And he gave some as apostles, some as prophets, some as evangelizers, some as shepherds and teachers.

00:03:50.539 --> 00:04:01.539
With a view to the re-adjustment of the Holy Ones, for ministerial work to build up the body of the Christ.

00:04:01.539 --> 00:04:11.539
Notice, they would be evangelizers, taking the lead in the all-important preaching and disciple-making work.

00:04:11.539 --> 00:04:17.540
They do not simply say to the publishers, go in the preaching work.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:21.540
They say, come, come with us.

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:26.540
Let's work together in this never-to-be-repeated work.

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:35.540
They are also shepherds, protecting the flock from Satan, the murderer, serpent, dragon, and lion.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:43.540
Additionally, they are teachers, feeding the flock with nourishing spiritual food.

00:04:43.540 --> 00:04:51.540
But now we ask, how does Jehovah tell us that we should feel about these hard-working gifts in men?

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:58.540
Let's go to 1 Thessalonians chapter 5, and let's get the answer.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:03.540
1 Thessalonians 5, beginning in verse number 12.

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:06.540
Notice what Jehovah says.

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:28.540
Now, we request you, brothers, to show respect for those who are working hard among you and presiding over you in the Lord and at monishing you and to give them extraordinary consideration in love because of their work.

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:32.540
Be peaceable with one another.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:39.540
Notice, we're told to show respect for these dear brothers.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:43.540
But now, let's move to a vital question.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:52.540
How can we show, demonstrate, that we do deeply respect and appreciate these dear brothers?

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:58.540
The first way, by whole-heartedly cooperating with them.

00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:05.540
Please turn to Hebrews chapter 13 and verse number 17.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:11.540
In this scripture describes how deep our cooperation should be.

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:36.790
Verse 17, be obedient to those who are taking the lead among you and be submissive for they are keeping watch over you as those who will render an account so that they may do this with joy and not with sighing for this would be damaging to you.

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:40.790
Notice, we are told to be obedient.

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:46.790
Clearly, this means that we're supposed to comply with or obey what they tell us.

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:53.790
Of course, that would be with a proviso, unless they tell us to do something that is unscriptual.

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:56.790
And, of course, that would be extremely rare.

00:06:56.790 --> 00:07:01.790
We're also told to be submissive.

00:07:01.790 --> 00:07:12.790
This includes the attitude with which we're to be obedient, doing so with a yielding, positive attitude.

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:17.790
Would it be possible to be obedient, but not submissive?

00:07:17.790 --> 00:07:24.790
Well, what if we said, okay, I'll do what the elders suggest.

00:07:24.790 --> 00:07:29.790
I don't want to do it, but I'll do it.

00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:33.790
We would be obedient, but not submissive.

00:07:33.790 --> 00:07:39.790
However, Jehovah tells us to display both of these qualities.

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:50.790
We should be obedient and submissive, even if what the elders are asking us to do is not the best, most efficient way to do something.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:53.790
Permit me to illustrate this point.

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:58.790
Admittedly, the illustration is somewhat exaggerated.

00:07:58.790 --> 00:08:01.790
But hopefully, it will make the point.

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:09.790
Please imagine that the elders decide that the outside of the kingdom hall needs to be painted,

00:08:09.790 --> 00:08:17.790
and that all the publishers will be given a small two-inch paintbrush with which to paint.

00:08:17.790 --> 00:08:19.790
Now, what could happen?

00:08:19.790 --> 00:08:25.790
The publishers could get all upset concerning this request of the elders saying,

00:08:25.790 --> 00:08:32.789
it is ridiculous that the elders want us to paint with a small two-inch paintbrush.

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:41.789
Consequently, some could start campaigning for the right for everyone to use a six-inch paintbrush.

00:08:41.789 --> 00:08:49.789
Others might campaign for using paint rollers to roll the paint on the kingdom hall.

00:08:49.789 --> 00:09:00.789
Still others might start trying to build support for renting and using a paint sprayer to spray the paint on the kingdom hall.

00:09:00.789 --> 00:09:08.789
In another camp, once might champion the idea of hiring out to a contractor, the painting of the kingdom hall.

00:09:08.789 --> 00:09:16.789
While another group is promoting the idea that the kingdom hall doesn't even need to be painted.

00:09:16.789 --> 00:09:19.789
Now, what would be the outcome?

00:09:19.789 --> 00:09:22.789
The congregation would be divided.

00:09:22.789 --> 00:09:25.789
The kingdom hall would never get painted.

00:09:25.789 --> 00:09:29.789
Publishers could end up stumbled right out of the truth.

00:09:29.789 --> 00:09:32.789
The elders would be very discouraged.

00:09:32.789 --> 00:09:35.789
Jehovah would be sad.

00:09:35.789 --> 00:09:39.789
And Satan would be made very happy.

00:09:40.789 --> 00:09:45.789
On the other hand, what if everyone humbly supported the elders?

00:09:45.789 --> 00:09:52.789
Perhaps thinking there's no scripture that says we can't paint with a two-inch paintbrush?

00:09:52.789 --> 00:10:00.789
In fact, Hebrews 13, 17 tells us to be obedient and submissive to the elders.

00:10:00.789 --> 00:10:04.789
So why don't we go ahead and support the elders?

00:10:04.789 --> 00:10:07.789
Now, what would be the outcome?

00:10:08.789 --> 00:10:11.789
The kingdom hall we get painted.

00:10:11.789 --> 00:10:20.789
The publishers would get to enjoy a lot of good association because they'd be working together for a long time.

00:10:20.789 --> 00:10:23.789
The elders would be very encouraged.

00:10:23.789 --> 00:10:26.789
Satan would be sad.

00:10:26.789 --> 00:10:31.789
And Jehovah's heart would be made glad.

00:10:31.789 --> 00:10:36.789
Well, what is the point of this hyperbole illustration?

00:10:36.789 --> 00:10:44.789
Being obedient and submissive to those taking the lead is much more important than how something is done.

00:10:44.789 --> 00:10:50.789
That is the attitude that Jehovah will richly bless.

00:10:50.789 --> 00:11:00.789
But now, a second way we can demonstrate that we deeply appreciate these dear brothers is to pray for that.

00:11:00.789 --> 00:11:11.789
Please note what the elder Paul urged the brothers to do for him at Romans 15, verse number 30.

00:11:11.789 --> 00:11:13.789
Here Paul said,

00:11:14.789 --> 00:11:31.789
Now, I urge you, brothers, through our Lord Jesus Christ and through the love of the Spirit that you exert yourselves with me in prayers to God for me.

00:11:31.789 --> 00:11:40.789
Paul recognized the power that he would derive as a result of others praying for him.

00:11:40.789 --> 00:11:44.789
And your local elders feel the same way.

00:11:44.789 --> 00:11:59.789
But the question is, in your personal private prayers, do you regularly thank Jehovah for your gifts and men and entreat Jehovah to richly supply them with his powerful Holy Spirit?

00:11:59.789 --> 00:12:09.789
Our answer to that question can reveal much about our appreciation for these hardworking elders.

00:12:09.789 --> 00:12:15.789
Now, let's move to a third way that we can demonstrate deep appreciation.

00:12:15.789 --> 00:12:21.789
We can do so by commending the elders.

00:12:21.789 --> 00:12:24.789
Here is a soul searching question.

00:12:24.789 --> 00:12:29.789
Do you periodically go up to various elders and say something like,

00:12:29.789 --> 00:12:34.789
Brother Elder, we just want to thank you for your hard work.

00:12:34.789 --> 00:12:38.789
Please be assured that we appreciate it.

00:12:38.789 --> 00:12:49.789
However, it seems that some publishers never, ever commend the elders or express appreciation.

00:12:49.789 --> 00:12:55.789
Might this not indicate that we are taking them in their hard work for granted?

00:12:55.789 --> 00:12:59.789
Of course, they will not quit if you do not give them commendation.

00:12:59.789 --> 00:13:03.789
They primarily do their work for Jehovah.

00:13:03.789 --> 00:13:11.789
But if you do express appreciation, believe me, it will be most encouraging to them.

00:13:11.789 --> 00:13:24.789
And even though it may really surprise the elder the very first time you do this, please do not hold back this good from those to whom it is owing.

00:13:24.789 --> 00:13:39.789
Appropriately, Jehovah tells us that Proverbs 327 do not withhold good from those to whom you should give it if it is within your power to help.

00:13:39.789 --> 00:13:47.789
And one thing that will move us to be more aware of commending the elders is to remember all the good work they are doing.

00:13:48.789 --> 00:13:55.789
Many elders are family men who must work securely to provide for their families.

00:13:55.789 --> 00:14:01.789
If he has children, these young ones need time and attention from their father.

00:14:01.789 --> 00:14:10.789
He may need to help them with their schoolwork, as well as schedule time for them to enjoy wholesome recreation.

00:14:10.789 --> 00:14:15.789
Most important, he cares for the spiritual needs of his family.

00:14:16.789 --> 00:14:23.789
Regularly conducting family worship, working with them in the ministry and taking them to meetings.

00:14:23.789 --> 00:14:34.789
But in addition to these numerous responsibilities common to many of us, they have voluminous additional responsibilities as elders.

00:14:34.789 --> 00:14:41.789
And much of the elders' hard work in our behalf is not seen by the congregation.

00:14:42.789 --> 00:14:46.789
For example, you may see an elder giving a part on the meeting.

00:14:46.789 --> 00:14:52.789
What you didn't see are the hours he spent preparing that part.

00:14:52.789 --> 00:15:00.789
How long does it take you to prepare a student assignment on the midweek meeting?

00:15:00.789 --> 00:15:05.789
Some elders have a part every week, sometimes more than one.

00:15:05.789 --> 00:15:16.789
While gaining experience and speaking is certainly helpful, the fact remains that good talks require hard work.

00:15:16.789 --> 00:15:19.789
But that is not all the elders do.

00:15:19.789 --> 00:15:25.789
They have shepherding costs to make, and judicial cases to handle.

00:15:25.789 --> 00:15:38.789
Some elders are also busy helping to build kingdom halls and branch facilities, serving on hospital liaison committees, volunteering at assemblies and conventions.

00:15:38.789 --> 00:15:44.789
And elders do many other things that are too numerous to recount.

00:15:45.789 --> 00:15:50.789
What we see is often only the tip of the iceberg.

00:15:50.789 --> 00:15:56.789
90% of an iceberg is unseen underwater.

00:15:56.789 --> 00:16:07.789
At 2 Timothy 4-6, the Apostle Paul referred to himself as being poured out like a drink offering.

00:16:08.789 --> 00:16:14.789
A drink offering was poured on the altar and went up in smoke.

00:16:14.789 --> 00:16:21.789
That well describes how the elders likewise expend themselves.

00:16:21.789 --> 00:16:31.789
Remembering all of this should move us to regularly offer sincere commendation to our hardworking elders.

00:16:32.789 --> 00:16:41.789
Now, we have discussed ways that we can demonstrate that we deeply appreciate our gifts and men.

00:16:41.789 --> 00:16:47.789
We should, number one, wholeheartedly cooperate with them.

00:16:47.789 --> 00:16:50.789
Number two, pray for them.

00:16:50.789 --> 00:16:53.789
Number three, commend them.

00:16:54.789 --> 00:17:08.789
We will prove that we are not even slightly like an unappreciative recipient of a silk tie or a silk scarf who uses that gift to polish his use.

00:17:08.789 --> 00:17:21.789
To the contrary, we will prove to Jehovah and Jesus that we love respect and appreciate the divine gifts or gifts and men

00:17:21.789 --> 00:17:28.039
that they have so generously given to us.

00:17:28.039 --> 00:17:39.039
But now, what effect can these gifts and men have on individuals who have strayed from Jehovah and his organization?

00:17:39.039 --> 00:17:52.039
What actions show that they are loving shepherds who want to assist these ones to return to Jehovah despite serious struggles or even addictions?

00:17:53.039 --> 00:17:59.319
Let's look for those answers in the following story.

00:17:59.319 --> 00:18:07.319
Turn your life around so that seasons of refreshing may come from Jehovah himself.

00:18:07.319 --> 00:18:13.319
Those words changed my life and they saved the life of my little girl.

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:30.900
I was raised in a witness family but I chose a dark underworld of practically everything that Jehovah hates.

00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:45.769
After about 15 years, although financially secure, I was confronted with the failure that my life had become.

00:18:45.769 --> 00:18:51.529
I was trying to raise a child while addicted to drugs.

00:18:51.529 --> 00:18:58.529
I just didn't want to live like that anymore and I wanted to be a good mother.

00:18:58.529 --> 00:19:03.529
So for the first time in years, I prayed to Jehovah.

00:19:03.529 --> 00:19:07.529
The knot came on my door the very next day.

00:19:07.529 --> 00:19:17.789
I began studying with a vengeance.

00:19:17.789 --> 00:19:22.420
I had 15 years to catch up on.

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:24.420
I had a lot of help.

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:27.420
I progressively changed my lifestyle.

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:32.420
I changed my associates and I conquered my addictions.

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:37.420
I slowly began to overcome feelings of worthlessness.

00:19:37.420 --> 00:19:48.309
So none of these changes were easy to make but it made me feel clean and happy knowing that Jehovah was pleased.

00:19:48.309 --> 00:19:54.309
My burning desire at that point really was to begin sharing with other people what I was learning.

00:19:54.309 --> 00:20:05.309
But I didn't qualify to engage in the public ministry because I was still living with my boyfriend at the time and he didn't understand some of the changes I was making.

00:20:05.309 --> 00:20:17.099
I was determined to turn my life around and overcome this last hurdle that was preventing me from serving Jehovah fully.

00:20:17.099 --> 00:20:23.099
Two weeks later, I found out I was pregnant.

00:20:23.099 --> 00:20:33.099
I was devastated. I didn't know what all those people who had helped me, what they would think, and how Jehovah felt about what was happening.

00:20:33.099 --> 00:20:38.589
I was so ashamed.

00:20:38.589 --> 00:20:42.589
I actually blamed Jehovah for letting it happen.

00:20:42.589 --> 00:20:45.589
I was so confused.

00:20:45.589 --> 00:20:51.589
My first inclination was just to get an abortion.

00:20:51.589 --> 00:20:54.589
But deep down I knew that was wrong.

00:20:54.589 --> 00:21:03.349
I thought now everyone would know that I'm still the worthless person that I always knew I was.

00:21:03.349 --> 00:21:08.299
At that point I just felt like giving up.

00:21:08.299 --> 00:21:14.299
I told my aunt and uncle, who are Jehovah's Witnesses, about my situation.

00:21:14.299 --> 00:21:23.299
They didn't judge me at all but they did offer a curious suggestion. They invited me up to Bethel for a visit.

00:21:23.299 --> 00:21:30.299
They introduced me to an elder who was very kind and I talked to him about my situation.

00:21:30.299 --> 00:21:38.299
I was shocked by how loving he was, so he shared with me Acts 319.

00:21:38.299 --> 00:21:42.299
Repent, therefore, and turn around.

00:21:42.299 --> 00:21:51.299
So as to get your sins blotted out, that seasons of refreshing may come from the person of Jehovah.

00:21:52.299 --> 00:21:57.299
Well, he told me, I had already sinned, but why should I sin a second time?

00:21:57.299 --> 00:22:01.299
Why should this innocent child pay for what I had done wrong?

00:22:01.299 --> 00:22:11.299
He suggested I teach my baby about Jehovah and raise the child up to know him and have a friendship with him.

00:22:11.299 --> 00:22:20.299
I loved that he took something that was sad and depressing for me and turned it into something beautiful.

00:22:21.299 --> 00:22:28.299
Well, I had a new plan now. I was really determined to do everything I had to do to turn my life around in order to please Jehovah.

00:22:28.299 --> 00:22:36.299
So eventually I qualified to become an unbaptized publisher and later I was baptized in 2010.

00:22:36.299 --> 00:22:40.299
I gave birth to a healthy baby girl.

00:22:40.299 --> 00:22:47.299
I already dedicated my life to Jehovah, so two of my goals are to get baptized and pioneered.

00:22:47.299 --> 00:22:55.299
I'm as determined as ever to raise Julie up to love Jehovah and to avoid the traps that almost cost us our lives.

00:22:55.299 --> 00:23:21.710
Describing our elders, Isaiah 322 reads, and each one will be like a hiding place from the wind, a place of concealment from the rainstorm, like streams of water in a waterless land.

00:23:21.710 --> 00:23:28.710
Like the shadow of a massive crag in a parched land.

00:23:28.710 --> 00:23:34.710
Did you note two key ways our gifts and men did that?

00:23:34.710 --> 00:23:41.710
One, the elder she met at Bethel was kind and approachable.

00:23:41.710 --> 00:23:46.710
He made her feel comfortable to express herself.

00:23:46.710 --> 00:23:55.710
Two, he lovingly used the Bible to help her make a wise decision and avoid further calamity.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:24:05.710
This is an excellent example of how elders can help ones who are struggling spiritually.

00:24:06.710 --> 00:24:14.710
But in what other ways can elders be an example in their zeal for the ministry?

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:19.710
But what if weather conditions in our territory make this difficult?

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:27.710
When the elders take the lead, the rest of the congregation respond in the same way.

00:24:28.710 --> 00:24:47.880
The example of those preaching in the Pharaoh Islands will offer some encouraging tips.

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:52.880
The Pharaoh Islands are also called the land of maybe.

00:24:52.880 --> 00:24:57.880
The weather is very diverse and can rapidly change.

00:24:57.880 --> 00:25:06.880
So when you begin in the ministry, the weather can be sunny and then 10 minutes later, you find yourself in a massive rain shower and everything gets wet.

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:10.880
When this another challenge, we have some severe winter storms.

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:20.630
So you have to be careful that your service partner or the car door doesn't blow away while you're getting out of the car.

00:25:20.630 --> 00:25:24.630
We make sure to wear clothes appropriate for the weather.

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:34.630
And also to keep updated on the weather situation and to see where in your territory the weather is most suitable and then adapt.

00:25:35.630 --> 00:25:38.630
If the weather is nice, then we try to go from house to house.

00:25:38.630 --> 00:25:47.630
And if the weather is bad, then you can go on calls where you can come inside, meaning weather will invite you in or where the entrance is covered.

00:25:47.630 --> 00:25:54.630
And you can plan your ministry so that if the weather gets bad, you can take visits that you know will be at home that time of day.

00:25:54.630 --> 00:25:59.170
When the weather is poor, it's good to adjust.

00:25:59.170 --> 00:26:03.170
Maybe you can do some telephone witnessing or letter writing.

00:26:04.170 --> 00:26:11.170
At a meeting for pioneers, an elder reminded us that when the weather is bad, try not to think the weather is bad again.

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:16.170
But instead, yay, now people are actually at home.

00:26:16.170 --> 00:26:22.170
It is a good idea to have a plan for whom you'd like to visit and what you'd like to talk to them about.

00:26:22.170 --> 00:26:32.170
Because then when it rains or the weather is an ideal, you focus on your plan instead of thinking that now I've been out preaching for five hours in stormy weather.

00:26:33.170 --> 00:26:38.170
I think Ecclesiastes 11-4 applies quite well to our territory.

00:26:38.170 --> 00:26:45.170
That the one who watches the wind will not so see, and the one who looks at the clouds will not reach.

00:26:45.170 --> 00:26:52.170
If we have to wait for the perfect weather conditions to preach, then we wouldn't be out that often.

00:26:52.170 --> 00:26:58.170
Something else that helps to endure bad weather is to think of the first publishers in the Faroe Islands.

00:26:58.170 --> 00:27:05.170
They fought with sea sickness, bad weather, and they had to hike over the mountains to visit remote settlements.

00:27:05.170 --> 00:27:12.170
They overcame these obstacles, and it motivates me to overcome the challenges I'm facing today.

00:27:12.170 --> 00:27:21.170
I remember when we came to the Faroe Islands. I looked out the window and thought, is it even possible to go out in the ministry in this kind of weather?

00:27:21.170 --> 00:27:29.170
And then we arrived at the Meeting for Field Service and the friends with children and strollers were there, and we're positive and ready for field service.

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:34.769
It made me think that if they can do it, then I can too.

00:27:34.769 --> 00:27:45.369
So we are a team of publishers and we have the weather as our challenge, and especially when the weather is bad, we encourage one another.

00:27:45.369 --> 00:27:51.369
We really like the song, The Life of a Pioneer. It's an amazing song.

00:27:51.369 --> 00:27:59.539
It says, in the work we endure with a sunshine or rain, because we loved Jehovah.

00:27:59.539 --> 00:28:05.539
We really want people to get to know Jehovah. They need to know the truth.

00:28:05.539 --> 00:28:13.539
When Jesus said that we should preach, I think that He also would have put on a raincoat and gone out to preach the good news.

00:28:13.539 --> 00:28:23.539
We experience how Jehovah blesses our efforts when we go in the ministry, and you especially feel it when you persist in your efforts to preach when the weather isn't good.

00:28:23.539 --> 00:28:29.539
It may be that one day you get a really nice conversation with a person about the Bible.

00:28:29.539 --> 00:28:36.539
I also feel it gives me great joy. Paul said that the one who soes bountifully will also reap bountifully.

00:28:36.539 --> 00:28:42.539
So if you want to sow bountifully in the Faroe Islands, you need to preach also when the weather is bad.

00:28:42.539 --> 00:28:47.539
And we feel that we have reaped bountifully by nice return visits and Bible studies.

00:28:47.539 --> 00:28:54.539
I feel as worth all the effort because we see that people in the territory really appreciate what they are learning.

00:28:54.539 --> 00:29:03.539
All we do in our ministry is motivated by love for Jehovah and the people in the territory, and it won't be changed by bad weather.

00:29:04.539 --> 00:29:08.539
It's an opportunity to show that our worship is wholehearted.

00:29:08.539 --> 00:29:12.539
You don't just go in the ministry when everything is good and the sun is shining.

00:29:12.539 --> 00:29:23.630
I think we have become more enduring and flexible in our ministry.

00:29:23.630 --> 00:29:34.630
We saw the publishers were fully supporting the spirit that the elders showed and sharing the good news despite inclement weather.

00:29:37.039 --> 00:29:50.039
Around the world, many of our brothers face severe opposition because of remaining loyal to Jehovah and maintaining their Christian neutrality.

00:29:50.039 --> 00:30:00.039
Let's travel to Spain and hear how some of our brothers have dealt with these challenges firsthand.

00:30:00.039 --> 00:30:05.670
Spain is a land of castles.

00:30:05.670 --> 00:30:13.670
For the mountains of central Spain to the Mediterranean coast, castles dominate the landscape.

00:30:13.670 --> 00:30:24.980
But there is one castle, the castle of Santa Catalina, that played a unique part in the history of Jehovah's Witnesses in Spain.

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:33.980
This castle, that guards the entrance to the harbor of Cadet in southern Spain, became a military prison over two centuries ago.

00:30:33.980 --> 00:30:39.980
And this fortress tested the faith of around 300 Spanish witnesses.

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:49.329
The battle began in the 1960s when Spain was ruled by General Fanco, a military dictator.

00:30:50.329 --> 00:30:57.329
Fanco wanted all Spanish men to serve the Fatherland and this meant military service.

00:30:57.329 --> 00:31:04.329
But in Spain, there were Jehovah's Witnesses whose conscience said no.

00:31:04.329 --> 00:31:14.329
So this castle became a battleground where Fanco's military regime fought to stamp out the Christian conscience of those young witnesses.

00:31:14.329 --> 00:31:20.440
But times have changed in Spain.

00:31:20.440 --> 00:31:28.440
The city of Cadet has organized an exhibition to salute the sacrifice made by those valiant witnesses.

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:38.440
Over 40 years after their release, some of those conscientious objectors have returned to Cadet to attend this exhibition.

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:54.440
At the inauguration, the mayor described them as citizens who spoke up, who presented arguments against the injustice, arguments based on peace, freedom and above all, their conscience.

00:31:54.440 --> 00:32:05.809
Those who spent years of their lives behind bars have vivid memories of the times when this castle was their prison.

00:32:05.809 --> 00:32:11.809
I think one of the greatest challenges was never knowing if we would be granted our freedom.

00:32:11.809 --> 00:32:17.150
Our first sentence was for three years.

00:32:17.150 --> 00:32:25.150
And since we still refused to enlist in the military, we were then sentenced again for another lengthy period.

00:32:25.150 --> 00:32:30.150
So it seemed as if we had a life sentence.

00:32:30.150 --> 00:32:34.150
We organized daily activities to keep us busy.

00:32:35.150 --> 00:32:40.150
Mornings, we worked at our trades to earn a little money.

00:32:40.150 --> 00:32:46.150
Afternoons, we set aside for spiritual activities.

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:51.690
Our preaching was unmainly by writing letters.

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:55.690
And in this way, some of us could even pioneer.

00:32:55.690 --> 00:33:04.690
A few people did reply to our letters and we were thrilled to hear that some of these accepted the truth.

00:33:04.690 --> 00:33:07.690
Of course, we also preached to other prisoners.

00:33:07.690 --> 00:33:11.690
And a few of them became baptized witnesses.

00:33:11.690 --> 00:33:20.690
We also studied the Bible thoroughly, both individually and as a group, which proved vital in building us up spiritually.

00:33:20.690 --> 00:33:24.690
At first, we had to study our literature secretly.

00:33:24.690 --> 00:33:32.160
But later, the guards allowed us to have the Bible and other publications.

00:33:32.160 --> 00:33:41.160
As our numbers grew, all the witnesses were kept together in the same place, in the same barracks, so we could organize meetings.

00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:46.700
We even held assemblies, including the biblical dramas.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:52.549
And we loved singing kindon songs.

00:33:52.549 --> 00:33:56.549
These songs really lifted up our spirits.

00:33:56.549 --> 00:34:04.440
We really felt Jehovah's loving care when the brothers came to visit us.

00:34:05.440 --> 00:34:12.300
We even had a special visit from Brother Kran Suta of the governing body.

00:34:12.300 --> 00:34:17.300
But there were also other visits that we really looked forward to.

00:34:17.300 --> 00:34:23.300
Many of the brothers endured years of separation from their families and fielses.

00:34:23.300 --> 00:34:25.300
This was a real test.

00:34:25.300 --> 00:34:31.300
But these faithful sisters wholeheartedly supported their neutral stand.

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:35.300
They were years that molded me spiritually.

00:34:36.300 --> 00:34:39.300
I studied the Bible as I had never done before.

00:34:39.300 --> 00:34:44.300
I developed the skills as a public speaker and as an overseer.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:51.300
Above all, it was a time in my life when I learned to rely totally on Jehovah.

00:34:51.300 --> 00:34:57.300
Thanks to my fervent prayers, he became my closest friend.

00:34:57.300 --> 00:35:00.300
And he never let me down.

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:02.300
That was priceless.

00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:09.300
The firm stand of those witnesses gave a powerful testimony in cadet and throughout Spain.

00:35:09.300 --> 00:35:15.300
The rundown military prison that once tested their faith has been restored.

00:35:15.300 --> 00:35:20.300
It is now a tourist attraction and a cultural center.

00:35:20.300 --> 00:35:28.300
But while the castle has changed, the faith of those valiant witnesses has not.

00:35:28.300 --> 00:35:31.300
The castle certainly tested them.

00:35:31.300 --> 00:35:34.300
But they fought a fine fight for the faith.

00:35:34.300 --> 00:35:39.300
And with Jehovah's help, they won the battle.

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:45.300
Forty years later, their victory is still giving a witness to Jehovah's name.

00:35:45.300 --> 00:35:58.260
As we noted earlier, the Apostle Paul said that he was being poured out like a drink offering.

00:35:58.260 --> 00:36:10.260
